{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17655781","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17655781"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:05:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:05:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18679"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18679","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18679"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11411"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76814"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11411","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11411"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18679"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62314"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10352"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26435"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26441"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76814","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76814"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe brainstem contains several groups of neurons that are essential for generating and controlling breathing patterns.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary respiratory rhythm generator in the brainstem?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Nucleus ambiguus in the pons","Pneumotaxic centre in the midbrain","Dorsal respiratory group in the pons","Pre-B\u00f6tzinger complex in the medulla","Apneustic centre in the cortex"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epre-B\u00f6tzinger complex in the medulla\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary respiratory rhythm generator, containing pacemaker neurons that establish the basic pattern of breathing. These neurons have intrinsic rhythmicity and form a network that generates the fundamental respiratory rhythm.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Enucleus ambiguus in the pons\u003C/strong\u003E primarily controls pharyngeal and laryngeal muscles for swallowing and vocalisation, not respiratory rhythm\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edorsal respiratory group in the pons\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrectly located - it is actually in the medulla and receives input from the rhythm generator\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epneumotaxic centre in the midbrain\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrectly located - it is in the pons and modulates respiratory rate but does not generate the basic rhythm\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eapneustic centre in the cortex\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrectly located - the apneustic centre is in the pons, and the cortex is not directly involved in basic respiratory rhythm generation\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe pre-B\u00f6tzinger complex works in conjunction with other respiratory centres to produce coordinated breathing patterns, but it is specifically responsible for generating the fundamental respiratory rhythm.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The pre-B\u00f6tzinger complex in the medulla generates the basic rhythm for breathing.","The dorsal respiratory group contains mainly inspiratory neurons that project to the phrenic nerve.","The ventral respiratory group contains both inspiratory and expiratory neurons that coordinate respiratory muscles."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62314"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18679"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62314","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62314"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T13:24:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T13:25:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11411"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76814"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Nervous System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024